      <bioghist id="aspace_7dc6d589eeab13dca41a8067c8afaf6b">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <chronlist>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1888 February 23</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Born in Tengchowfu, Shandong (Shantung) Province, China - son of Presbyterian missionaries Watson MacMillan Hayes and Margaret Young Hayes</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1910</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>A.B., Princeton University</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1911</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Appointed Rhodes Scholar from Ohio as candidate from Wooster College (x'09)</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1914</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>B.A., Oxford University, England</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1914</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Service with YMCA in France</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1916</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Married Barbara M. Kelman</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1917</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>B.D., Princeton Theological Seminary</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1917</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Presbyterian Church in the U.S.A. missionary in China. Hayes was in charge of Presbyterian student Christian work in Beijing (Peking), China, 1917-1943. He was also Executive Chairman of the American Presbyterian Mission, member of the China Council, member of the Board of Directors of Yenching University, and on various other boards for many years.</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1918</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Involved in various flood and famine relief projects</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1925</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Served on faculty and administration of College of Chinese Studies, Beijing (Peking)</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>NaN</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Interned by Japanese authorities in Weihsien Civilian Assembly Centre, Shandong (Shantung) Province.</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1948</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Returned to China, serving in Kueiyang, Kweichow Province.</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1949</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Taught at government university following Communist takeover</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>NaN</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Jailed by Communists</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1955</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Went to Indonesia to work with students</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
            <chronitem>
               <datesingle>1957</datesingle>
               <chronitemset>
                  <event>Died from injuries suffered in an automobile accident in Indonesia</event>
               </chronitemset>
            </chronitem>
         </chronlist>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_b1b3d20dd163ef294cae0ac529294184">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>Hayes' work with students in China, his administrative work, and his work in famine and flood relief are described in biographical accounts. Of particular interest are Hayes' writings regarding his period of Japanese internment and the "confessions" that Hayes was forced to write while imprisoned by the Communists.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_e6361fdc7b3a76e0f6604d5fd04e6641">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <list listtype="unordered">
            <item>I. Biographical documentation</item>
            <item>II. Writings</item>
            <item>III. Collected material</item>
            <item>IV. Audio-visual material</item>
         </list>
      </arrangement>
      <processinfo id="aspace_566b0569b4298cbe1076928d197114fc">
         <head>Processing Information</head>
         <p>Place names were modernized in the description, with the name originally used in the collection material or in an older version of the finding aid in parenthesis: e.g. "Beijing (Peking)" or "Benin (Dahomey)".</p>  
      </processinfo>
